CatDescriptText: Moses Jones, steelmill worker, 1137 River Street, Braddock, was part of the "Pittsburghers Speak Up" column published in Pittsburgh Courier newspaper, August 8, 1959, pg. B1 with question: "Do you believe the John James Racket Squad is driving the numbers racket out of Pittsburgh?" answer reads: "No. I think that it is pretty hard to drive out the numbers racket.  It is set to last a long time, because it has a good root and a lot of good people are backing it up."
TitMainTitle: Portrait of Moses Jones wearing eyeglasses and short sleeved fine paisley shirt with eyeglasses case in chest pocket, standing outside of Jenkins Arcade, with Thrift Drugs and Kappels in background, Liberty Avenue, Downtown
